{"title_page": "Halifa Sallah", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix   = \n | name               = Halifa Sallah\n | honorific-suffix   = \n | image              = Halifa Sallah 2016.png\n | image_size         = \n | office             = [[President of the Gambia|Special Advisor to the President on Governance]]\n | term_start         = 17 February 2017\n | term_end           = March 2017\n | predecessor        =\n | successor          = \n | president          = [[Adama Barrow]]\n | office1             = [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly Minority Leader]]\n | term_start1         = 17 January 2002\n | term_end1           = 25 January 2007\n | predecessor1        = Kemesseng Jammeh\n | successor1          = [[Momodou L. K. Sanneh]]\n | office2             = [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly]] Member\n | term_start2         = 6 April 2017\n | term_end2           =\n | constituency2       = [[Serekunda]]\n | predecessor2        =\n | successor2          = \n | term_start3         = 17 January 2002\n | term_end3           = 25 January 2007\n | constituency3       = Serekunda Central\n | predecessor3        =\n | successor3          = [[Fabakary Jatta]]\n | office4             = Secretary-General of the [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism]]\n | term_start4         = August 1987\n | term_end4           = \n | predecessor4        =\n | successor4          = \n | birth_name      = \n | birth_date      = {{Birth year and age|1953}}\n | birth_place     = [[Serekunda]], [[the Gambia]]\n | citizenship     = \n | nationality     = \n | party           = [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism|PDOIS]]\n | otherparty      = [[National Alliance for Democracy and Development|NADD]]<br />[[Coalition 2016]]\n | height          =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | mother          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | father          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | relatives       = \n | residence       = \n | education       = \n | alma_mater      = \n}}\n\n'''Halifa Sallah''' (born 1953) is a Gambian politician who is currently a member of the [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly]] representing [[Serekunda]], and the secretary-general of the [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism]] (PDOIS). He served as a spokesman and advisor to [[President of the Gambia|President]] [[Adama Barrow]] from during the [[2016 Gambian presidential election|2016 presidential election]] campaign until March 2017.\n\nSallah co-founded PDOIS in 1986, and was elected as its secretary-general in 1987. He has been a major contributor to ''[[Foroyaa]]'', the party's newspaper. He contested elections for the [[House of Representatives of the Gambia|House of Representatives]] in 1987 and 1992, and was an opposer of the [[Yahya Jammeh]] regime. He stood unsuccessfully for the National Assembly in 1997, but was elected in 2002, serving until 2007. During that time, he also served as Minority Leader. Sallah has also served in the [[Pan-African Parliament]], and was the [[National Alliance for Democracy and Development]] (NADD)'s candidate for president in the [[2006 Gambian presidential election|2006 presidential election]], coming third with 6% of the vote.\n\n== Early life ==\nSallah was born and raised in [[Serekunda]], [[the Gambia]], and was educated in the [[United States]], graduating with a degree in sociology.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06BANJUL548_a.html|title=Gambian Presidential Election - Candidate Profiles|last=|first=|date=5 September 2006|website=WikiLeaks|publisher=|access-date=21 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://jollofnews.com/2016/02/24/gambia-s-halifa-sallah-to-lead-pdois-in-dec-poll/|title=Gambia\u2019s Halifa Sallah To Lead PDOIS In Dec. Poll|last=|first=|date=24 February 2016|work=Jollof News|access-date=21 January 2017|via=}}</ref> He returned to the Gambia in 1977 and worked as a social worker in the Social Welfare Department.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of the Gambia|last=Perfect|first=David|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2016|isbn=|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=374\u2013375|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Jawara era and post-coup ===\nAfter returning from the United States in the late 1970s, Sallah became involved with the People's Movement for Independence against Neo-Colonialism and Capitalism (PMINCC). It is also believed that he was one of the editors of ''The Voice of the Future'' newspaper. Along with other PMINCC members, he was arrested in October 1983 and went on trial in 1984 for his involvement in distributing ''The Voice''. He was acquitted but lost his job as a result of the trial.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 1986, Sallah was one of the founders of the [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism]] (PDOIS). He was elected as its secretary-general in August 1987. He also became a major contributor to its newspaper, ''[[Foroyaa]]'', which he co-edited with [[Sidia Jatta]].<ref name=\"Detained\">{{cite news|url=http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/gambia-opposition-leader-detained-2009061930057.html|title=Gambia opposition leader detained|work=Panapress|access-date=June 19, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621233727/http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/gambia-opposition-leader-detained-2009061930057.html|archive-date=June 21, 2009|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Sallah contested the Serekunda East constituency in the 1987 and 1992 elections for the [[National Assembly of the Gambia|House of Representatives]], but only won around 10% of the vote. Following [[Yahya Jammeh]]'s [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]] in 1994, Sallah and other PDOIS leaders adopted a principled stance in response, with Sallah and Jatta both turning down offers to join the [[Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council]]. Both men were detained in August 1994 for publishing an edition of ''Foroyaa'' despite the ban on political activities. They were put on trial, found guilty, and fined, but resumed publication in November 1994 as a non-partisan newspaper.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Parliamentary career, arrest and presidential campaign ===\nSallah again unsuccessfully contested the Serekunda East constituency in the [[1997 Gambian parliamentary election|1997 election]] but was elected to the new constituency of Serekunda Central in the [[2002 Gambian parliamentary election|2002 parliamentary election]]. As the [[United Democratic Party (Gambia)|United Democratic Party]] (UDP) had boycotted the election, the PDOIS, with two seats, emerged as the largest opposition party, and Sallah became the Minority Leader in the National Assembly. He also served as a member of the [[Pan-African Parliament]] in this period. In June 2005, he was expelled from the National Assembly along with three other opposition MPs on the grounds of dual party membership. [[National Alliance for Democracy and Development|NADD]], an opposition alliance that the PDOIS had joined earlier that year, had been registered as a political party, and the Supreme Court of the Gambia ruled that holding dual membership was against the Gambian Constitution. Some criticised the ruling, claiming that it was a move to silence parliamentary opposition as there was nothing in the Constitution that regulated political parties. On 29 September, a by-election was held in Serrekunda Central, in which Sallah was re-elected by a \"huge\" margin.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.africansuccess.org/visuFiche.php?lang=en&id=673|title=Biography of Halifa SALLAH|last=|first=|date=|website=African Success|publisher=|access-date=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 November 2005, he was arrested along with two other opposition leaders on the grounds of subversion, accused of having collaborated with the [[President of Senegal]]. The charges, however, were dropped following the intervention of [[Olusegun Obasanjo]], then-[[President of Nigeria]]. Sallah was NADD's candidate in the [[2006 Gambian presidential election|2006 presidential election]], where he came third and won 5.98% of the vote. During the election, the US Embassy described Sallah as \"known and respected throughout the country and abroad for his constant admonishment of President Jammeh's government for its failure to adhere to the country's constitution and the principles of democracy.\" They also wrote: \"A win by Halifa Sallah would almost certainly usher in a new era in Gambian government and politics. Sallah's ideas are consistent with democratic principles and we would expect a Sallah administration to be a reliable friend of the US.\"<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Further arrests, 2016 campaign and Barrow presidency ===\nHe lost his seat in the National Assembly in the [[2007 Gambian parliamentary election|2007 parliamentary election]] to Sainey Jaiteh, a member of the ruling [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]]. While not mentioning Sallah by name, [[Yahya Jammeh]] made a coded reference to him and [[Hamat Bah]] when he expressed his satisfaction at the defeat of \"the two empty barrels in the National Assembly\". Sallah blamed the opposition's poor performance in the election on a split in its ranks and said that he intended to retire from politics and concentrate on writing.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afrol.com/articles/24072|title=Gambian President laughs at opponents|publisher=afrol News|date=January 29, 2007|accessdate=August 21, 2008}}</ref> On 8 March 2009, Sallah was arrested and taken to the central prison, Mile II. The Jammeh regime accused him of spying.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200903240775.html|title=Gambia: Leave Halifa Sallah Alone|website=[[allafrica.com]]|date=March 24, 2009|accessdate=April 7, 2009}}</ref> However, the charges were dropped against him on 25 March \"in the interest of peace and justice\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foroyaa.gm/modules/news/article.php?storyid=2079|title=Foroyaa: \"Charges Against Halifa Sallah Dropped|author=Fabakary B. Ceesay|date=March 20, 2009|access-date=April 8, 2009|archive-date=July 21, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721031835/http://www.foroyaa.gm/modules/news/article.php?storyid=2079|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Sallah was also reportedly detained in June 2009, when he went to visit a group of imprisoned journalists at the [[National Intelligence Agency (Gambia)|National Intelligence Agency]].<ref name=\"Detained\" /> He was held overnight before being released on bail.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/opposition-leader,-journalist-released-on-bail-2009062030127.html |title=Opposition leader, journalist released on bail |work=Panapress |access-date=June 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319060936/http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/opposition-leader,-journalist-released-on-bail-2009062030127.html |archive-date=March 19, 2012 }}</ref> Before the [[2011 Gambian presidential election]], Sallah released a statement saying he would not be a candidate because \"the office of President or Vice President is not of value to [him]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/office-of-president-not-of-value-to-halifa-sallah|title=Office of President not of value to Halifa Sallah|last=|first=|date=31 October 2011|work=The Point|access-date=21 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, it was announced that Sallah would be PDOIS's candidate in the [[2016 Gambian presidential election]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He later became the spokesperson for [[Coalition 2016]], and following Jammeh's defeat by [[Adama Barrow]] in the election, declared that Jammeh would be treated like a \"rebel leader\" if he did not relinquish control by 19 January 2017, when his term ended.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/halifa-sallah-warns-that-jammeh-will-be-treated-like-a-rebel-leader-if-he-fails-to-handover/|title=Halifa Sallah Warns That Jammeh Will Be Treated Like A Rebel Leader If He Fails To Handover|last=|first=|date=|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=21 January 2017|via=}}</ref> Sallah remained the coalition spokesperson following Barrow's election. It was rumored that Sallah was being considered for [[Vice-President of the Gambia|Vice-President]] by Barrow, but Barrow changed his mind following a meeting with [[Ousainou Darboe]] and other UDP members. Sallah subsequently declined the offer of a cabinet position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://whatson-gambia.com/news/headline-news/1735-halifa-sallah-declines-cabinet-position-in-barrow-administration|title=Halifa Sallah declines cabinet position in Barrow administration|last=|first=|date=8 February 2017|work=What's on Gambia|access-date=6 March 2017}}</ref> On 17 February 2017, Sallah was appointed as Special Advisor to the President on Governance (but he never take the role). SMBC News commented that his \"appointment will bring absolute, total, complete confidence of the Barrow administration.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gambia.smbcgo.com/2017/02/17/halifa-sallah-president-barrows-special-advisor-governance/|title=Halifa Sallah is President Barrow\u2019s Special Advisor on Governance |last=|first=|date=17 February 2017|newspaper=SMBC News|access-date=18 February 2017|work=|via=}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2017, Sallah announced that he would be contesting the [[2017 Gambian parliamentary election|2017 parliamentary election]] to the National Assembly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gambia.smbcgo.com/2017/02/24/halifa-sallah-seek-serrekunda-east-parliamentary-seat/|title=Halifa Sallah to seek Serrekunda East parliamentary seat|last=|first=|date=24 February 2017|work=SMBC News|access-date=6 March 2017}}</ref> Upon submitting his nomination to the Independent Electoral Commission, he said that it would be the duty of the incoming NAMs to build up the National Assembly as an oversight institution.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://foroyaa.gm/national-assembly-nominations-we-want-to-build-up-the-national-assembly-halifa-sallah/|title=NATIONAL ASSEMBLY NOMINATIONS \u2018We Want to Build up the National Assembly\u2019, Halifa Sallah|last=|first=|date=13 March 2017|work=Foroyaa|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> Sallah also resigned from his executive role as an advisor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.allgambianews.com/2017/11/13/gambia-halifa-not-take-govt-job/|title=Gambia: This is why Halifa did not take a Govt Job|last=|first=|date=13 November 2017|work=All Gambia News|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> He stood in the constituency of Serekunda and was duly elected. In August, Sallah called for a debate with Ousainou Darboe, the leader of the [[United Democratic Party (Gambia)|United Democratic Party]] (UDP), over the credibility of Coalition 2016's memorandum of understanding stating that Barrow would only serve for three years, instead of a full five years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://freedomnewspaper.com/2017/08/24/gambia-breaking-news-halifa-sallah-challenges-foreign-minister-darboe-to-a-grts-debate-over-barrows-three-years-transition-govt/|title=Breaking News: Halifa Sallah Challenges Foreign Minister Darboe To A GRTS Debate Over Barrow\u2019s Three Years Transition Gov\u2019t|last=|first=|date=24 August 2017|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Sallah said that the Barrow government was \"reminiscent of the APRC government days\" as \"nothing seems to have improved the living standard of ordinary Gambians.\" The Office of the President issued a statement in response stating that \"Comparing this government to the former dictatorial regime is a distortion of facts.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/barrow-hits-back-at-halifa|title=Barrow hits back at Halifa|last=|first=|date=20 October 2017|work=The Point|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> Sallah visited [[Ohio University]] for three days in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ohio.edu/compass/stories/17-18/02/Halifa-Sallah-visit-to-OHIO.cfm|title=Political leader from The Gambia to visit OHIO|last=|first=|date=14 February 2018|work=Compass|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> On 8 March, Sallah met with the Cuban Ambassador to The Gambia, L\u00e1zaro Herrera, in his home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://misiones.minrex.gob.cu/en/articulo/meeting-secretary-general-pdois|title=Meeting with the Secretary General of PDOIS|last=|first=|date=8 March 2018|website=Cuban Embassies|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> On 16 March, during a heated exchange over a proposed loan from [[China]], Sallah was removed from the National Assembly on the orders of Speaker [[Mariam Jack-Denton]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://foroyaa.gm/heated-exchange-between-the-speaker-and-halifa-sallah/|title=Heated Exchange between the Speaker and Halifa Sallah|last=|first=|date=16 March 2018|work=Foroyaa|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSallah was involved in a car accident while touring the country in March 2016 and \"suffered cuts to his face\", but his injuries were not life-threatening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/gambia-breaking-news-halifa-sallah-involved-car-accident-conditions-not-life-threatening/|title=Halifa Sallah Involved In A Car Accident; His Conditions Not Life Threatening|last=|first=|date=|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=21 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nGambia's political scientist, Amat Jeng, writes this about him:\n\"Born in Serrekunda and educated in the US, Halifa Sallah returned home in the 1970s during the turbulent days of pan-Africanism and the Cold War, totally appalled at capitalism, neo-colonialism and the racism he saw in the US. Part of the founding fathers of the \u2018Red Star\u2019, commonly known as the People's Movement for Independence against Neo-Colonialism and Capitalism (PMINCC), Sallah began to espouse social democracy, believing that for a nation to realize its political and social freedoms, the masses have to, first, be free from external and internal oppression and domination, and second, be educated to become masters of state and society. For thirty years, Halifa was popular with the educated few, but failed massively to win the support of the masses, because they never understood his politics.\"<ref>http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/opinion-sallahism-and-de-jammehnisation-of-gambian-politics</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sallah, Halifa}}\n[[Category:Gambian democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pan-African Parliament from the Gambia]]\n[[Category:People from Serekunda]]\n[[Category:People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism politicians]]\n[[Category:Gambian socialists]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in the Gambia]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific-prefix   = \n | name               = Halifa Sallah\n | honorific-suffix   = \n | image              = Halifa Sallah 2016.png\n | image_size         = \n | office             = [[President of the Gambia|Special Advisor to the President on Governance]]\n | term_start         = 17 February 2017\n | term_end           = March 2017\n | predecessor        =\n | successor          = \n | president          = [[Adama Barrow]]\n | office1             = [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly Minority Leader]]\n | term_start1         = 17 January 2002\n | term_end1           = 25 January 2007\n | predecessor1        = Kemesseng Jammeh\n | successor1          = [[Momodou L. K. Sanneh]]\n | office2             = [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly]] Member\n | term_start2         = 6 April 2017\n | term_end2           =\n | constituency2       = [[Serekunda]]\n | predecessor2        =\n | successor2          = \n | term_start3         = 17 January 2002\n | term_end3           = 25 January 2007\n | constituency3       = Serekunda Central\n | predecessor3        =\n | successor3          = [[Fabakary Jatta]]\n | office4             = Secretary-General of the [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism]]\n | term_start4         = August 1987\n | term_end4           = \n | predecessor4        =\n | successor4          = \n | birth_name      = \n | birth_date      = {{Birth year and age|1953}}\n | birth_place     = [[Serekunda]], [[the Gambia]]\n | citizenship     = \n | nationality     = \n | party           = [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism|PDOIS]]\n | otherparty      = [[National Alliance for Democracy and Development|NADD]]<br />[[Coalition 2016]]\n | height          =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n | spouse          = \n | partner         =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n | relations       = \n | children        = \n | parents         =  <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n | mother          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | father          =  <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n | relatives       = \n | residence       = \n | education       = \n | alma_mater      = \n}}\n\n'''Halifa Sallah''' (born 1953) is a Gambian politician who is currently a member of the [[National Assembly of the Gambia|National Assembly]] representing [[Serekunda]], and the secretary-general of the [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism]] (PDOIS). He served as a spokesman and advisor to [[President of the Gambia|President]] [[Adama Barrow]] from during the [[2016 Gambian presidential election|2016 presidential election]] campaign until March 2017.\n\nSallah co-founded PDOIS in 1986, and was elected as its secretary-general in 1987. He has been a major contributor to ''[[Foroyaa]]'', the party's newspaper. He contested elections for the [[House of Representatives of the Gambia|House of Representatives]] in 1987 and 1992, and was an opposer of the [[Yahya Jammeh]] regime. He stood unsuccessfully for the National Assembly in 1997, but was elected in 2002, serving until 2007. During that time, he also served as Minority Leader. Sallah has also served in the [[Pan-African Parliament]], and was the [[National Alliance for Democracy and Development]] (NADD)'s candidate for President in the [[2006 Gambian presidential election|2006 presidential election]], coming third with 6% of the vote.\n\n== Early life ==\nSallah was born and raised in [[Serekunda]], [[the Gambia]], and was educated in the [[United States]], graduating with a degree in sociology.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06BANJUL548_a.html|title=Gambian Presidential Election - Candidate Profiles|last=|first=|date=5 September 2006|website=WikiLeaks|publisher=|access-date=21 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://jollofnews.com/2016/02/24/gambia-s-halifa-sallah-to-lead-pdois-in-dec-poll/|title=Gambia\u2019s Halifa Sallah To Lead PDOIS In Dec. Poll|last=|first=|date=24 February 2016|work=Jollof News|access-date=21 January 2017|via=}}</ref> He returned to the Gambia in 1977 and worked as a social worker in the Social Welfare Department.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of the Gambia|last=Perfect|first=David|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2016|isbn=|location=Lanham, Maryland|pages=374\u2013375|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Jawara era and post-coup ===\nAfter returning from the United States in the late 1970s, Sallah became involved with the People's Movement for Independence against Neo-Colonialism and Capitalism (PMINCC). It is also believed that he was one of the editors of ''The Voice of the Future'' newspaper. Along with other PMINCC members, he was arrested in October 1983 and went on trial in 1984 for his involvement in distributing ''The Voice''. He was acquitted but lost his job as a result of the trial.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 1986, Sallah was one of the founders of the [[People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism]] (PDOIS). He was elected as its secretary-general in August 1987. He also became a major contributor to its newspaper, ''[[Foroyaa]]'', which he co-edited with [[Sidia Jatta]].<ref name=\"Detained\">{{cite news|url=http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/gambia-opposition-leader-detained-2009061930057.html|title=Gambia opposition leader detained|work=Panapress|access-date=June 19, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621233727/http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/gambia-opposition-leader-detained-2009061930057.html|archive-date=June 21, 2009|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Sallah contested the Serekunda East constituency in the 1987 and 1992 elections for the [[National Assembly of the Gambia|House of Representatives]], but only won around 10% of the vote. Following [[Yahya Jammeh]]'s [[1994 Gambian coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]] in 1994, Sallah and other PDOIS leaders adopted a principled stance in response, with Sallah and Jatta both turning down offers to join the [[Armed Forces Provisional Ruling Council]]. Both men were detained in August 1994 for publishing an edition of ''Foroyaa'' despite the ban on political activities. They were put on trial, found guilty, and fined, but resumed publication in November 1994 as a non-partisan newspaper.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Parliamentary career, arrest and presidential campaign ===\nSallah again unsuccessfully contested the Serekunda East constituency in the [[1997 Gambian parliamentary election|1997 election]] but was elected to the new constituency of Serekunda Central in the [[2002 Gambian parliamentary election|2002 parliamentary election]]. As the [[United Democratic Party (Gambia)|United Democratic Party]] (UDP) had boycotted the election, the PDOIS, with two seats, emerged as the largest opposition party, and Sallah became the Minority Leader in the National Assembly. He also served as a member of the [[Pan-African Parliament]] in this period. In June 2005, he was expelled from the National Assembly along with three other opposition MPs on the grounds of dual party membership. [[National Alliance for Democracy and Development|NADD]], an opposition alliance that the PDOIS had joined earlier that year, had been registered as a political party, and the Supreme Court of the Gambia ruled that holding dual membership was against the Gambian Constitution. Some criticised the ruling, claiming that it was a move to silence parliamentary opposition as there was nothing in the Constitution that regulated political parties. On 29 September, a by-election was held in Serrekunda Central, in which Sallah was re-elected by a \"huge\" margin.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.africansuccess.org/visuFiche.php?lang=en&id=673|title=Biography of Halifa SALLAH|last=|first=|date=|website=African Success|publisher=|access-date=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 November 2005, he was arrested along with two other opposition leaders on the grounds of subversion, accused of having collaborated with the [[President of Senegal]]. The charges, however, were dropped following the intervention of [[Olusegun Obasanjo]], then-[[President of Nigeria]]. Sallah was NADD's candidate in the [[2006 Gambian presidential election|2006 presidential election]], where he came third and won 5.98% of the vote. During the election, the US Embassy described Sallah as \"known and respected throughout the country and abroad for his constant admonishment of President Jammeh's government for its failure to adhere to the country's constitution and the principles of democracy.\" They also wrote: \"A win by Halifa Sallah would almost certainly usher in a new era in Gambian government and politics. Sallah's ideas are consistent with democratic principles and we would expect a Sallah administration to be a reliable friend of the US.\"<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Further arrests, 2016 campaign and Barrow presidency ===\nHe lost his seat in the National Assembly in the [[2007 Gambian parliamentary election|2007 parliamentary election]] to Sainey Jaiteh, a member of the ruling [[Alliance for Patriotic Reorientation and Construction|APRC]]. While not mentioning Sallah by name, [[Yahya Jammeh]] made a coded reference to him and [[Hamat Bah]] when he expressed his satisfaction at the defeat of \"the two empty barrels in the National Assembly\". Sallah blamed the opposition's poor performance in the election on a split in its ranks and said that he intended to retire from politics and concentrate on writing.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afrol.com/articles/24072|title=Gambian President laughs at opponents|publisher=afrol News|date=January 29, 2007|accessdate=August 21, 2008}}</ref> On 8 March 2009, Sallah was arrested and taken to the central prison, Mile II. The Jammeh regime accused him of spying.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200903240775.html|title=Gambia: Leave Halifa Sallah Alone|website=[[allafrica.com]]|date=March 24, 2009|accessdate=April 7, 2009}}</ref> However, the charges were dropped against him on 25 March \"in the interest of peace and justice\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foroyaa.gm/modules/news/article.php?storyid=2079|title=Foroyaa: \"Charges Against Halifa Sallah Dropped|author=Fabakary B. Ceesay|date=March 20, 2009|access-date=April 8, 2009|archive-date=July 21, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721031835/http://www.foroyaa.gm/modules/news/article.php?storyid=2079|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Sallah was also reportedly detained in June 2009, when he went to visit a group of imprisoned journalists at the [[National Intelligence Agency (Gambia)|National Intelligence Agency]].<ref name=\"Detained\" /> He was held overnight before being released on bail.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/opposition-leader,-journalist-released-on-bail-2009062030127.html |title=Opposition leader, journalist released on bail |work=Panapress |access-date=June 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319060936/http://www.afriquejet.com/news/africa-news/opposition-leader,-journalist-released-on-bail-2009062030127.html |archive-date=March 19, 2012 }}</ref> Before the [[2011 Gambian presidential election]], Sallah released a statement saying he would not be a candidate because \"the office of President or Vice President is not of value to [him]\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/office-of-president-not-of-value-to-halifa-sallah|title=Office of President not of value to Halifa Sallah|last=|first=|date=31 October 2011|work=The Point|access-date=21 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, it was announced that Sallah would be PDOIS's candidate in the [[2016 Gambian presidential election]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He later became the spokesperson for [[Coalition 2016]], and following Jammeh's defeat by [[Adama Barrow]] in the election, declared that Jammeh would be treated like a \"rebel leader\" if he did not relinquish control by 19 January 2017, when his term ended.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/halifa-sallah-warns-that-jammeh-will-be-treated-like-a-rebel-leader-if-he-fails-to-handover/|title=Halifa Sallah Warns That Jammeh Will Be Treated Like A Rebel Leader If He Fails To Handover|last=|first=|date=|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=21 January 2017|via=}}</ref> Sallah remained the coalition spokesperson following Barrow's election. It was rumored that Sallah was being considered for [[Vice-President of the Gambia|Vice-President]] by Barrow, but Barrow changed his mind following a meeting with [[Ousainou Darboe]] and other UDP members. Sallah subsequently declined the offer of a cabinet position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://whatson-gambia.com/news/headline-news/1735-halifa-sallah-declines-cabinet-position-in-barrow-administration|title=Halifa Sallah declines cabinet position in Barrow administration|last=|first=|date=8 February 2017|work=What's on Gambia|access-date=6 March 2017}}</ref> On 17 February 2017, Sallah was appointed as Special Advisor to the President on Governance (but he never take the role). SMBC News commented that his \"appointment will bring absolute, total, complete confidence of the Barrow administration.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gambia.smbcgo.com/2017/02/17/halifa-sallah-president-barrows-special-advisor-governance/|title=Halifa Sallah is President Barrow\u2019s Special Advisor on Governance |last=|first=|date=17 February 2017|newspaper=SMBC News|access-date=18 February 2017|work=|via=}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2017, Sallah announced that he would be contesting the [[2017 Gambian parliamentary election|2017 parliamentary election]] to the National Assembly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gambia.smbcgo.com/2017/02/24/halifa-sallah-seek-serrekunda-east-parliamentary-seat/|title=Halifa Sallah to seek Serrekunda East parliamentary seat|last=|first=|date=24 February 2017|work=SMBC News|access-date=6 March 2017}}</ref> Upon submitting his nomination to the Independent Electoral Commission, he said that it would be the duty of the incoming NAMs to build up the National Assembly as an oversight institution.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://foroyaa.gm/national-assembly-nominations-we-want-to-build-up-the-national-assembly-halifa-sallah/|title=NATIONAL ASSEMBLY NOMINATIONS \u2018We Want to Build up the National Assembly\u2019, Halifa Sallah|last=|first=|date=13 March 2017|work=Foroyaa|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> Sallah also resigned from his executive role as an advisor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.allgambianews.com/2017/11/13/gambia-halifa-not-take-govt-job/|title=Gambia: This is why Halifa did not take a Govt Job|last=|first=|date=13 November 2017|work=All Gambia News|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> He stood in the constituency of Serekunda and was duly elected. In August, Sallah called for a debate with Ousainou Darboe, the leader of the [[United Democratic Party (Gambia)|United Democratic Party]] (UDP), over the credibility of Coalition 2016's memorandum of understanding stating that Barrow would only serve for three years, instead of a full five years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://freedomnewspaper.com/2017/08/24/gambia-breaking-news-halifa-sallah-challenges-foreign-minister-darboe-to-a-grts-debate-over-barrows-three-years-transition-govt/|title=Breaking News: Halifa Sallah Challenges Foreign Minister Darboe To A GRTS Debate Over Barrow\u2019s Three Years Transition Gov\u2019t|last=|first=|date=24 August 2017|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Sallah said that the Barrow government was \"reminiscent of the APRC government days\" as \"nothing seems to have improved the living standard of ordinary Gambians.\" The Office of the President issued a statement in response stating that \"Comparing this government to the former dictatorial regime is a distortion of facts.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/barrow-hits-back-at-halifa|title=Barrow hits back at Halifa|last=|first=|date=20 October 2017|work=The Point|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> Sallah visited [[Ohio University]] for three days in February 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ohio.edu/compass/stories/17-18/02/Halifa-Sallah-visit-to-OHIO.cfm|title=Political leader from The Gambia to visit OHIO|last=|first=|date=14 February 2018|work=Compass|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> On 8 March, Sallah met with the Cuban Ambassador to The Gambia, L\u00e1zaro Herrera, in his home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://misiones.minrex.gob.cu/en/articulo/meeting-secretary-general-pdois|title=Meeting with the Secretary General of PDOIS|last=|first=|date=8 March 2018|website=Cuban Embassies|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref> On 16 March, during a heated exchange over a proposed loan from [[China]], Sallah was removed from the National Assembly on the orders of Speaker [[Mariam Jack-Denton]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://foroyaa.gm/heated-exchange-between-the-speaker-and-halifa-sallah/|title=Heated Exchange between the Speaker and Halifa Sallah|last=|first=|date=16 March 2018|work=Foroyaa|access-date=12 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSallah was involved in a car accident while touring the country in March 2016 and \"suffered cuts to his face\", but his injuries were not life-threatening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.freedomnewspaper.com/gambia-breaking-news-halifa-sallah-involved-car-accident-conditions-not-life-threatening/|title=Halifa Sallah Involved In A Car Accident; His Conditions Not Life Threatening|last=|first=|date=|work=Freedom Newspaper|access-date=21 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nGambia's political scientist, Amat Jeng, writes this about him:\n\"Born in Serrekunda and educated in the US, Halifa Sallah returned home in the 1970s during the turbulent days of pan-Africanism and the Cold War, totally appalled at capitalism, neo-colonialism and the racism he saw in the US. Part of the founding fathers of the \u2018Red Star\u2019, commonly known as the People\u2019s Movement for Independence against Neo-Colonialism and Capitalism (PMINCC), Sallah began to espouse social democracy, believing that for a nation to realize its political and social freedoms, the masses have to, first, be free from external and internal oppression and domination, and second, be educated to become masters of state and society. For thirty years, Halifa was popular with the educated few, but failed massively to win the support of the masses, because they never understood his politics.\"<ref>http://thepoint.gm/africa/gambia/article/opinion-sallahism-and-de-jammehnisation-of-gambian-politics</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sallah, Halifa}}\n[[Category:Gambian democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pan-African Parliament from the Gambia]]\n[[Category:People from Serekunda]]\n[[Category:People's Democratic Organisation for Independence and Socialism politicians]]\n[[Category:Gambian socialists]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in the Gambia]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo(s) fixed: President \u2192 president, \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halifa_Sallah"}
{"title_page": "Dejan Kulusevski", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Dejan Kulusevski\n| image = Dejan Kulusevski 2019.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Kulusevski in 2019\n| full_name = Dejan Kulusevski\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|04|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| height = 1.86 m\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (on loan from [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]])\n| clubnumber = 44\n| youthyears1 = 2006\u20132016\n| youthclubs1 = [[IF Brommapojkarna|Brommapojkarna]]\n| youthyears2 = 2016\u20132019\n| youthclubs2 = [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]\n| years1 = 2018\u20132020\n| clubs1 = [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]\n| caps1 = 3\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 22\n| goals2 = 5\n| years3 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n| caps3 = 0\n| goals3 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\n| nationalteam1 = [[North Macedonia national under-17 football team|Macedonia U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 5\n| nationalgoals1 = 6\n| nationalyears2 = 2015\u20132017\n| nationalteam2 = [[Sweden national under-17 football team|Sweden U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 19\n| nationalgoals2 = 6\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam3 = [[Sweden national under-19 football team|Sweden U19]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 13\n| nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 5\n| nationalgoals4 = 2\n| nationalyears5 = 2019\u2013 \n| nationalteam5 = [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] \n| nationalcaps5 = 1 \n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| pcupdate = 10:56, 21 February 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 18 November 2019\n}}\n'''Dejan Kulusevski'''  ({{lang-mk|\u0414\u0435\u0458\u0430\u043d \u041a\u0443\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438}}, {{IPA-mk|\u02c8d\u025bjan kulu\u02c8\u0283\u025bvski|pron}}; born 25 April 2000) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{Italian football updater|Parma}} club [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]], on loan from [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], and the [[Sweden national football team|Sweden national team]].<ref name=\"SW\">{{Soccerway|dejan-kulusevski/460405}}</ref> Born in Sweden to [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian]] parents, Kulusevski chose to represent his native country internationally at senior level, and made his full debut in 2019.\n\nComing through from the youth system, Kulusevski made his senior debut for [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] in 2019, before joining Parma on loan at the beginning of the [[2019\u201320 Serie A|2019\u201320 season]]. With four goals and seven assists in 17 league games, Kulusevski joined Juventus during the winter transfer window for \u20ac35 million and was sent back to Parma on loan for the rest of the season.\n\nKulusevski is a quick, physical, and technical player, capable of playing in various midfield and attacking positions. Mainly deployed as a [[Midfielder#Winger|right-winger]], he can also play as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], as an offensive\u2013minded [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] or \"half-winger\" (''[[Midfielder#Mezzala|mezzala]]'' in Italian), or as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre-forward]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nKulusevski was born in [[V\u00e4llingby]], a suburb to [[Stockholm]], and joined the youth academy of [[IF Brommapojkarna]] at the age of 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atalanta.it/site/paginalive/giovanili/Stagione-2017-2018/2017-10/11-10-Primavera-alla-scoperta-di-Kulusevski.html|title=Primavera: alla scoperta di... Dejan Kulusevski|website=www.atalanta.it|language=Italian|date=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Atalanta===\n====2018\u201319: Debut season====\nHe joined [[Atalanta B.C. Youth Sector|Atalanta youth system]] (under 17 squad) on 7 July 2016 from Brommapojkarna. He made his [[Serie A]] debut on 20 January 2019, coming on as a substitute for [[Marten de Roon]] in a 5\u20130 away win against [[Frosinone Calcio|Frosinone]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/commentary?gameId=522618 |title=Frosinone 0\u20135 Atalanta |publisher=ESPN FC |date=20 January 2019 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"UEFA Profile\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2637649.html |title=Who is new Juventus signing Dejan Kulusevski? |publisher=UEFA.com |date=2 January 2020 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref> He made a total of three appearances for the club throughout the 2018\u201319 season, each as a substitute.<ref name=\"Juventus agree deal\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/dec/31/juventus-agree-deal-to-sign-19-year-old-midfielder-dejan-kulusevski-for-30m |title=Juventus agree deal to sign 19-year-old midfielder Dejan Kulusevski for \u00a330m |work=The Guardian |last1=Romano |first1=Fabrizio |date=31 December 2019 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n====2019: First loan to Parma====\nOn 18 July 2019, Kulusevski signed to [[Serie A]] club [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] on loan until 30 June 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.tuttomercatoweb.com/serie-a/ufficiale-parma-presi-cornelius-e-kulusevski-dall-atalanta-1270279|access-date=18 July 2019|title=UFFICIALE: Parma, presi Cornelius e Kulusevski dall'Atalanta}}</ref> He scored his first Serie A goal in a 3\u20132 home win against [[Torino F.C.|Torino]], on 30 September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/6jdw6W|title=Ny succ\u00e9 f\u00f6r Dejan Kulusevski \u2013 f\u00f6rsta m\u00e5let i Serie A|website=Aftonbladet|language=sv|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> On 14 December 2019, Kulusevski scored his fourth league goal, against Napoli; he became the youngest player in the top five leagues in Europe to have scored more than three goals to date.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/it/news/news/2020/dejan-kulusevski---un-giocatore-della-juventus-.php|title=Dejan Kulusevski \u00e8 un giocatore della Juventus!|website=Juventus.com|language=Italian|date=2 January 2020|access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref> He was also one of two players born after 1 January 1999, alongside [[Jadon Sancho]], to have made at least seven assists in the top five European leagues.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n===Juventus===\n====2020: Second loan to Parma====\nFollowing his form while on loan with Parma during the first part of the [[2019\u201320 Serie A]] season, during which he scored four goals and provided seven assists in 17 league appearances, on 2 January 2020, Kulusevski joined fellow Serie A club [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] on a four-and-a-half year deal, for \u20ac35 million, which could possibly rise to \u20ac44 million with variables. Kulusevski was sent back on loan to Parma for the remainder of the season.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==International career==\nBorn in Sweden to [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian]] parents, Kulusevski played for all Swedish youth national teams,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballscouting.it/atalanta/alla-scoperta-di-dejan-kulusevski-il-predestinato-dellatalanta-che-verra/|title=Alla scoperta di Dejan Kulusevski, il \"predestinato\" dell'Atalanta che verr\u00e0 {{!}} Football Scouting|last=|first=|date=17 November 2018|website=Football Scouting {{!}} Campionato Primavera {{!}} Calcio Giovanile|language=it-IT|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.calciomercato.com/news/kulusevski-trascina-l-atalanta-soffiato-all-arsenal-studia-da-nu-93777|title=Kulusevski trascina l'Atalanta: soffiato all'Arsenal, studia da nuovo-Cristante|website=Calciomercato.com {{!}} Tutte le news sul calcio in tempo reale|language=it|access-date=20 January 2019}}</ref> as well as the [[North Macedonia national under-17 football team|North Macedonia under-16 national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/serie-a/ufficiale-atalanta-tesserata-la-stellina-kulusevski-851664|title=UFFICIALE: Atalanta, tesserata la stellina Kulusevski - TUTTOmercatoWEB.com|website=www.tuttomercatoweb.com|language=it|access-date=20 January 2019}}</ref> He was called up to the [[Sweden national football team|Sweden national team]] for the first time in November 2019 for the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] games against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/sport/fotboll/landslaget/dejan-kulusevski-uttagen-efter-succen/|title=Dejan Kulusevski uttagen i landslaget efter j\u00e4ttesucc\u00e9n|website=www.expressen.se|language=sv|access-date=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nKulusevski made his senior international debut for Sweden on 18 November, coming on as a substitute for [[Ken Sema]] in a 3\u20130 win against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] in the last game of the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying|Euro 2020 qualifying]] stage.<ref name=\"Juventus agree deal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fotbollskanalen.se/sverige/nerver-gav-tunga-ben-i-debuten-for-kulusevski---som-sagar-planen-den-var-inte-/|title=Nerver gav tunga ben i debuten f\u00f6r Kulusevski - som s\u00e5gar planen: \"Den var inte okej\"|publisher=www.fotbollskanalen.se|language=Swedish|last=Petersson|first=Martin|date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA tall, physical, and versatile player, Kulusevski is capable of playing in several [[Midfielder|midfield]] and [[Forward (association football)|attacking]] roles, and has been deployed as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], as a [[Midfielder#Box-to-box midfielder|box-to-box midfielder]], as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] on either flank, or even as an offensive-minded central midfielder, known as the ''mezzala'' role in Italian (literally \"half\u2013winger\"); his favoured position is playing as an attacking midfielder behind the striker. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/stories/highlights/18069418999128118/|title=FR\u00c5GESTUNDER - @sweu21|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> He has also been deployed as a makeshift centre-forward on occasion. His main qualities are his acceleration, speed, stamina, and his ability to switch the play or provide assists and through balls to teammates, courtesy of his vision and passing ability. He also possesses good technique, [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] skills, and striking ability, which enables him to score goals, in addition to creating chances for teammates.<ref name=\"UEFA Profile\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldfootballscouting.com/giovani-talenti-del-2000/dejan-kulusevski-talento-svedese-classe-2000/ |title=Dejan Kulusevski: talento svedese classe 2000 |publisher=www.worldfootballscouting.com |language=Italian |date=31 October 2018 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/148188/kulusevski-perfect-juve-future |title=Kulusevski perfect for Juve future |publisher=Football Italia |last1=Yakimov |first1=Vilizar |date=2 January 2020 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/serie-a/parma/2019/10/25-62633317/parma_d_aversa_kulusevski_centravanti_quel_ruolo_l_ha_fatto_/ |title=Parma, D'Aversa: \"Kulusevski centravanti? Quel ruolo l'ha fatto...\" |work=Tutto Sport |language=Italian |date=25 October 2019 |accessdate=3 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nRegarded as a promising and hard-working player in the media, his manager at Parma, [[Roberto D'Aversa]], has compared Kulusevski to [[Mohamed Salah]]. He noted how the player \"is always among the players who cover the most distance in every game\", and \"has the right mentality\".<ref name=\"UEFA Profile\" /> Kulusevski himself named compatriot [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]] as an influence.<ref name=\"UEFA Profile\" /> Regarding his own playing style, he commented in a 2019 interview with ''[[Sportbladet]]'': \"I like to have the ball at my feet. I used to dribble a lot when I was a kid but I have got better at moving the ball more quickly. I have developed my defensive game, that was a weakness before, and that has made me a more complete player.\"<ref name=\"Juventus agree deal\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/sportbladet/fotboll/a/opxbja/jag-kanner-mig-speciell |title=Kulusevski i stor intervju: \u201dK\u00e4nner mig speciell\u201d |publisher=www.aftonbladet.se |language=Swedish |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 15 February 2020}}<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|[[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Serie A|2018\u201319]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Serie A]]\n|3||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||3||0\n|-\n|[[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (loan)\n|[[2019\u201320 Serie A|2019\u201320]]\n|22||5||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||25||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!25!!5!!3!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!28!!5\n|}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|18 November 2019}}<ref name=\"SW\"/><ref name=\"NFT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.national-football-teams.com/player/76259/Dejan_Kulusevski.html |title=Kulusevski, Dejan |publisher=www.national-football-teams.com |accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref>\n{|class = \"wikitable\" style = \"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |[[Sweden national football team|Sweden national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2019||1||0\n|-\n!Total||1||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Atalanta'''<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n* [[Coppa Italia]] runner-up: [[2018\u201319 Coppa Italia|2018\u201319]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT player|76259}}\n* {{Soccerway|460405}}\n* {{Svenskfotboll|711462}}\n\n{{Parma Calcio 1913 squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kulusevski, Dejan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:Macedonian footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden international footballers]]\n[[Category:North Macedonia youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Macedonian descent]]\n[[Category:Atalanta B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Parma Calcio 1913 players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Dejan Kulusevski\n| image = Dejan Kulusevski 2019.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Kulusevski in 2019\n| full_name = Dejan Kulusevski\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|04|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| height = 1.86 m\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (on loan from [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]])\n| clubnumber = 44\n| youthyears1 = 2006\u20132016\n| youthclubs1 = [[IF Brommapojkarna|Brommapojkarna]]\n| youthyears2 = 2016\u20132019\n| youthclubs2 = [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]\n| years1 = 2018\u20132020\n| clubs1 = [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]\n| caps1 = 3\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2019\u20132020\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 17\n| goals2 = 4\n| years3 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs3 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n| caps3 = 0\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 5\n| goals4 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\n| nationalteam1 = [[North Macedonia national under-17 football team|Macedonia U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 5\n| nationalgoals1 = 6\n| nationalyears2 = 2015\u20132017\n| nationalteam2 = [[Sweden national under-17 football team|Sweden U17]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 19\n| nationalgoals2 = 6\n| nationalyears3 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam3 = [[Sweden national under-19 football team|Sweden U19]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 13\n| nationalgoals3 = 2\n| nationalyears4 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden U21]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 5\n| nationalgoals4 = 2\n| nationalyears5 = 2019\u2013 \n| nationalteam5 = [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] \n| nationalcaps5 = 1 \n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n| pcupdate = 10:56, 21 February 2020 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 18 November 2019\n}}\n'''Dejan Kulusevski'''  ({{lang-mk|\u0414\u0435\u0458\u0430\u043d \u041a\u0443\u043b\u0443\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438}}, {{IPA-mk|\u02c8d\u025bjan kulu\u02c8\u0283\u025bvski|pron}}; born 25 April 2000) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{Italian football updater|Parma}} club [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]], on loan from [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]], and the [[Sweden national football team|Sweden national team]].<ref name=\"SW\">{{Soccerway|dejan-kulusevski/460405}}</ref> Born in Sweden to [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian]] parents, Kulusevski chose to represent his native country internationally at senior level, and made his full debut in 2019.\n\nComing through from the youth system, Kulusevski made his senior debut for [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]] in 2019, before joining Parma on loan at the beginning of the [[2019\u201320 Serie A|2019\u201320 season]]. With four goals and seven assists in 17 league games, Kulusevski joined Juventus during the winter transfer window for \u20ac35 million and was sent back to Parma on loan for the rest of the season.\n\nKulusevski is a quick, physical, and technical player, capable of playing in various midfield and attacking positions. Mainly deployed as a [[Midfielder#Winger|right-winger]], he can also play as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], as an offensive\u2013minded [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] or \"half-winger\" (''[[Midfielder#Mezzala|mezzala]]'' in Italian), or as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre-forward]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nKulusevski was born in [[V\u00e4llingby]], a suburb to [[Stockholm]], and joined the youth academy of [[IF Brommapojkarna]] at the age of 6.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atalanta.it/site/paginalive/giovanili/Stagione-2017-2018/2017-10/11-10-Primavera-alla-scoperta-di-Kulusevski.html|title=Primavera: alla scoperta di... Dejan Kulusevski|website=www.atalanta.it|language=Italian|date=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Atalanta===\n====2018\u201319: Debut season====\nHe joined [[Atalanta B.C. Youth Sector|Atalanta youth system]] (under 17 squad) on 7 July 2016 from Brommapojkarna. He made his [[Serie A]] debut on 20 January 2019, coming on as a substitute for [[Marten de Roon]] in a 5\u20130 away win against [[Frosinone Calcio|Frosinone]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/commentary?gameId=522618 |title=Frosinone 0\u20135 Atalanta |publisher=ESPN FC |date=20 January 2019 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"UEFA Profile\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2637649.html |title=Who is new Juventus signing Dejan Kulusevski? |publisher=UEFA.com |date=2 January 2020 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref> He made a total of three appearances for the club throughout the 2018\u201319 season, each as a substitute.<ref name=\"Juventus agree deal\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/dec/31/juventus-agree-deal-to-sign-19-year-old-midfielder-dejan-kulusevski-for-30m |title=Juventus agree deal to sign 19-year-old midfielder Dejan Kulusevski for \u00a330m |work=The Guardian |last1=Romano |first1=Fabrizio |date=31 December 2019 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n====2019: First loan to Parma====\nOn 18 July 2019, Kulusevski signed to [[Serie A]] club [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] on loan until 30 June 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.tuttomercatoweb.com/serie-a/ufficiale-parma-presi-cornelius-e-kulusevski-dall-atalanta-1270279|access-date=18 July 2019|title=UFFICIALE: Parma, presi Cornelius e Kulusevski dall'Atalanta}}</ref> He scored his first Serie A goal in a 3\u20132 home win against [[Torino F.C.|Torino]], on 30 September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/6jdw6W|title=Ny succ\u00e9 f\u00f6r Dejan Kulusevski \u2013 f\u00f6rsta m\u00e5let i Serie A|website=Aftonbladet|language=sv|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref> On 14 December 2019, Kulusevski scored his fourth league goal, against Napoli; he became the youngest player in the top five leagues in Europe to have scored more than three goals to date.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/it/news/news/2020/dejan-kulusevski---un-giocatore-della-juventus-.php|title=Dejan Kulusevski \u00e8 un giocatore della Juventus!|website=Juventus.com|language=Italian|date=2 January 2020|access-date=2 January 2020}}</ref> He was also one of two players born after 1 January 1999, alongside [[Jadon Sancho]], to have made at least seven assists in the top five European leagues.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n===Juventus===\n====2020: Second loan to Parma====\nFollowing his form while on loan with Parma during the first part of the [[2019\u201320 Serie A]] season, during which he scored four goals and provided seven assists in 17 league appearances, on 2 January 2020, Kulusevski joined fellow Serie A club [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] on a four-and-a-half year deal, for \u20ac35 million, which could possibly rise to \u20ac44 million with variables. Kulusevski was sent back on loan to Parma for the remainder of the season.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==International career==\nBorn in Sweden to [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonian]] parents, Kulusevski played for all Swedish youth national teams,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.footballscouting.it/atalanta/alla-scoperta-di-dejan-kulusevski-il-predestinato-dellatalanta-che-verra/|title=Alla scoperta di Dejan Kulusevski, il \"predestinato\" dell'Atalanta che verr\u00e0 {{!}} Football Scouting|last=|first=|date=17 November 2018|website=Football Scouting {{!}} Campionato Primavera {{!}} Calcio Giovanile|language=it-IT|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.calciomercato.com/news/kulusevski-trascina-l-atalanta-soffiato-all-arsenal-studia-da-nu-93777|title=Kulusevski trascina l'Atalanta: soffiato all'Arsenal, studia da nuovo-Cristante|website=Calciomercato.com {{!}} Tutte le news sul calcio in tempo reale|language=it|access-date=20 January 2019}}</ref> as well as the [[North Macedonia national under-17 football team|North Macedonia under-16 national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/serie-a/ufficiale-atalanta-tesserata-la-stellina-kulusevski-851664|title=UFFICIALE: Atalanta, tesserata la stellina Kulusevski - TUTTOmercatoWEB.com|website=www.tuttomercatoweb.com|language=it|access-date=20 January 2019}}</ref> He was called up to the [[Sweden national football team|Sweden national team]] for the first time in November 2019 for the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]] games against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] and the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/sport/fotboll/landslaget/dejan-kulusevski-uttagen-efter-succen/|title=Dejan Kulusevski uttagen i landslaget efter j\u00e4ttesucc\u00e9n|website=www.expressen.se|language=sv|access-date=6 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nKulusevski made his senior international debut for Sweden on 18 November, coming on as a substitute for [[Ken Sema]] in a 3\u20130 win against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] in the last game of the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying|Euro 2020 qualifying]] stage.<ref name=\"Juventus agree deal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fotbollskanalen.se/sverige/nerver-gav-tunga-ben-i-debuten-for-kulusevski---som-sagar-planen-den-var-inte-/|title=Nerver gav tunga ben i debuten f\u00f6r Kulusevski - som s\u00e5gar planen: \"Den var inte okej\"|publisher=www.fotbollskanalen.se|language=Swedish|last=Petersson|first=Martin|date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA tall, physical, and versatile player, Kulusevski is capable of playing in several [[Midfielder|midfield]] and [[Forward (association football)|attacking]] roles, and has been deployed as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], as a [[Midfielder#Box-to-box midfielder|box-to-box midfielder]], as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] on either flank, or even as an offensive-minded central midfielder, known as the ''mezzala'' role in Italian (literally \"half\u2013winger\"); his favoured position is playing as an attacking midfielder behind the striker. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/stories/highlights/18069418999128118/|title=FR\u00c5GESTUNDER - @sweu21|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> He has also been deployed as a makeshift centre-forward on occasion. His main qualities are his acceleration, speed, stamina, and his ability to switch the play or provide assists and through balls to teammates, courtesy of his vision and passing ability. He also possesses good technique, [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] skills, and striking ability, which enables him to score goals, in addition to creating chances for teammates.<ref name=\"UEFA Profile\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldfootballscouting.com/giovani-talenti-del-2000/dejan-kulusevski-talento-svedese-classe-2000/ |title=Dejan Kulusevski: talento svedese classe 2000 |publisher=www.worldfootballscouting.com |language=Italian |date=31 October 2018 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/148188/kulusevski-perfect-juve-future |title=Kulusevski perfect for Juve future |publisher=Football Italia |last1=Yakimov |first1=Vilizar |date=2 January 2020 |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/serie-a/parma/2019/10/25-62633317/parma_d_aversa_kulusevski_centravanti_quel_ruolo_l_ha_fatto_/ |title=Parma, D'Aversa: \"Kulusevski centravanti? Quel ruolo l'ha fatto...\" |work=Tutto Sport |language=Italian |date=25 October 2019 |accessdate=3 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nRegarded as a promising and hard-working player in the media, his manager at Parma, [[Roberto D'Aversa]], has compared Kulusevski to [[Mohamed Salah]]. He noted how the player \"is always among the players who cover the most distance in every game\", and \"has the right mentality\".<ref name=\"UEFA Profile\" /> Kulusevski himself named compatriot [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]] as an influence.<ref name=\"UEFA Profile\" /> Regarding his own playing style, he commented in a 2019 interview with ''[[Sportbladet]]'': \"I like to have the ball at my feet. I used to dribble a lot when I was a kid but I have got better at moving the ball more quickly. I have developed my defensive game, that was a weakness before, and that has made me a more complete player.\"<ref name=\"Juventus agree deal\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/sportbladet/fotboll/a/opxbja/jag-kanner-mig-speciell |title=Kulusevski i stor intervju: \u201dK\u00e4nner mig speciell\u201d |publisher=www.aftonbladet.se |language=Swedish |accessdate=2 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 15 February 2020}}<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|[[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Serie A|2018\u201319]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Serie A]]\n|3||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||3||0\n|-\n|[[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] (loan)\n|[[2019\u201320 Serie A|2019\u201320]]\n|22||5||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||colspan=\"2\"|\u2013||25||5\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!25!!5!!3!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!28!!5\n|}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|18 November 2019}}<ref name=\"SW\"/><ref name=\"NFT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.national-football-teams.com/player/76259/Dejan_Kulusevski.html |title=Kulusevski, Dejan |publisher=www.national-football-teams.com |accessdate=29 December 2019 }}</ref>\n{|class = \"wikitable\" style = \"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" |[[Sweden national football team|Sweden national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2019||1||0\n|-\n!Total||1||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Atalanta'''<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n* [[Coppa Italia]] runner-up: [[2018\u201319 Coppa Italia|2018\u201319]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT player|76259}}\n* {{Soccerway|460405}}\n* {{Svenskfotboll|711462}}\n\n{{Parma Calcio 1913 squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kulusevski, Dejan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:Macedonian footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden international footballers]]\n[[Category:North Macedonia youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Macedonian descent]]\n[[Category:Atalanta B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Parma Calcio 1913 players]]\n[[Category:Juventus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n", "name_user": "Sweupdate", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dejan_Kulusevski"}
{"title_page": "4 (New York City Subway service)", "text_new": "{{for|the former Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation 4 service|N (New York City Subway service)}}\n{{Infobox NYCS service\n| service    = 4\n| name       = Lexington Avenue Express\n| image1     = 4 train leaving Harlem on August night.jpg\n| size1 = 250px\n| caption1 = Bronx-bound 4 train of [[R142A (New York City Subway car)|R142As]] leaving [[125th Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|125th Street]].\n| north term = [[Woodlawn (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|Woodlawn]]\n| south term = [[Crown Heights\u2013Utica Avenue (IRT Eastern Parkway Line)|Crown Heights\u2013Utica Avenue]] (daytime) <br />[[New Lots Avenue (IRT New Lots Line)|New Lots Avenue]] (late nights & limited rush hour service)\n| stations   = 28<br />54 (late night service)\n| note       = dashed line shows late night and limited weekday rush hour service to/from [[New Lots Avenue (IRT New Lots Line)|New Lots Avenue]]\n| depot      = [[Jerome Yard|Jerome Avenue Yard]]\n| started    = {{start date and age|1917|06|02}}\n| map        = {{4 (New York City Subway service)}}\n| map_state  = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''4 Lexington Avenue Express'''<ref name=\"timetable\">{{NYCS const|timetable|4}}</ref> is a [[rapid transit]] service in the [[A Division (New York City Subway)|A Division]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Its route emblem, or \"bullet\", is colored {{NYCS const|color|green}} since it uses the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] in [[Manhattan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/developers/resources/line_colors.htm|title=mta.info &#124; Line Colors|website=web.mta.info}}</ref>\n\nThe 4 operates at all times. Daytime service operates between [[Woodlawn (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|Woodlawn]] in [[the Bronx]] and [[Crown Heights\u2013Utica Avenue (IRT Eastern Parkway Line)|Utica Avenue]] in [[Crown Heights, Brooklyn]], via [[IRT Jerome Avenue Line|Jerome Avenue Local]] in the Bronx, Lexington Avenue Express in Manhattan, and [[IRT Eastern Parkway Line|Eastern Parkway Express]] in Brooklyn; limited rush hour service, as well as late night service, is extended beyond Utica Avenue to/from [[New Lots Avenue (IRT New Lots Line)|New Lots Avenue]] in [[East New York, Brooklyn]] via [[IRT New Lots Line|Livonia Avenue]]. During rush hours in the peak direction, 4 trains skip [[138th Street\u2013Grand Concourse (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|138th Street\u2013Grand Concourse]].{{efn|Trains skip 138th Street southbound between 6:52 and 9 a.m. and skip it northbound between 4:50 and 6:25 p.m.|name=138th Street}} Late night service makes all stops except for [[Hoyt Street (IRT Eastern Parkway Line)|Hoyt Street]]. For up to an hour after evening events that are held at [[Yankee Stadium]], a special downtown-only express service runs between {{Station|161st Street\u2013Yankee Stadium}} and {{Station|Bowling Green}}.\n\nUntil 1983, rush hour 4 trains originated and terminated at [[Flatbush Avenue\u2013Brooklyn College (IRT Nostrand Avenue Line)|Flatbush Avenue\u2013Brooklyn College]] in [[Brooklyn]].\n\n== Service history ==\n\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\">\n{| width=\"80\"\n[[File:R12 IRT 4.gif|64px]]\n|-\n|<div class=\"thumbcaption\"> Original [[R12 (New York City Subway car)|R12]] to [[R36 (New York City Subway car)|R36]] end rollsign</div>\n|}\n</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\">\n{| width=\"80\"\n[[File:4 (1967-1979 New York City Subway bullet).svg]]\n|-\n|<div class=\"thumbcaption\">November 26, 1967-June 1979 bullet</div>\n|}\n</div>\n\n===Under the Interborough Rapid Transit===\nService on what was later known as the 4 began on June 2, 1917, as the first portion of the [[IRT Jerome Avenue Line]] opened between 149th Street\u2014Grand Concourse and Kingsbridge Road. Since the extension of the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] between 149th Street and Grand Central was not yet open, this section was served by shuttle trains using elevated train cars.<ref name=\"erictb.info\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.erictb.info/linehistory.html|title=NYCT Line by Line History|website=erictb.info|access-date=September 23, 2016}}</ref> On April 15, 1918, with the extension of the Jerome Avenue Line to Woodlawn, shuttle service was also extended. On July 17, 1918, the Lexington Avenue Line local tracks were opened, allowing another shuttle service to run between 149th Street\u2013Grand Concourse and Grand Central. On August 1, 1918, the entire Jerome and Lexington Avenue Lines were completed and the connection to the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] at 42nd Street was removed. Trains began running between 167th Street and Bowling Green, with shuttles to Woodlawn.<ref name=\"erictb.info\" />\n\nOn December 11, 1921, Lexington Avenue\u2013Jerome Avenue subway trains began running north of [[167th Street station (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|167th Street]] at all times, replacing elevated trains, which ran to Woodlawn during rush hours, but from then on terminated at 167th Street during non-rush hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pudl.princeton.edu/sheetreader.php?obj=e75de858-4334-4238-bc92-399e37286bbb|title=An Improvement in Service for Passengers on the Jerome Avenue Line North of 167th Street|last=|first=|date=December 11, 1921|website=pudl.princeton.edu|publisher=Interborough Rapid Transit Company|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt a hearing of the New York State Transit Commission on October 15, 1924 about where it planned to allocate the second hundred of 350 new steel cars, it was announced that service on the IRT Eastern Parkway Line from Atlantic Avenue to Livonia Avenue was almost certainly going to be increased by 25 to 50% in the coming six to eight weeks. Two options were discussed at the hearing. The commission, in response to intense requests from riders on the line, called for the introduction of express service between Atlantic Avenue and Utica Avenue on tracks which had been unused since the line's opening in 1920. It proposed extending half of 4 trains from Atlantic Avenue to New Lots Avenue, running express to Utica Avenue. The introduction of express service would have made it possible to run 30 more trains per hour east of Atlantic Avenue (27 trains per hour had been operating), decreasing overcrowding from 325% to 185%. The plan preferred by the IRT was to place 70 cars on the West Side Line for service to Flatbush Avenue, and Pennsylvania Avenue and New Lots Avenue, and 40 additional cars for service along Eastern Parkway.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35414638/times-union/|title=I.R.T. Will Get Increased Service To Livonia Avenue: Practically Certain That 100 New Cars Will Be Put on Eastern Parkway Line.|date=October 16, 1924|work=Brooklyn Times Union|access-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOn November 17, 1924, the Transit Commission ordered the IRT to use 100 new subway cars to increase service by no later than December 1. Among the changes in service ordered was the operation of through service on the 4 between Kingsbridge Road and Woodlawn, eliminating shuttle service.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35414795/times-union/|title=Transit Board Orders I.R.T. To Increase Service: Demands More Trains in Rush Hour by Use of New Cars.|date=November 17, 1924|work=Brooklyn Times Union|access-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This change was made possible by 20 of the new cars.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35414748/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=100 I.R.T. Cars To Be Used On Borough Lines|date=November 17, 1924|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Transit Commission headed the IRT's recommendation not to have half of 4 trains run express due to the dangerous operating condition it would have created. The IRT stated that two minutes would not be enough time to turn around trains terminating at Atlantic Avenue while maintaining the headway between trains and that this service pattern would risk train collisions. Operating this service pattern would have required 2 minutes and 45 seconds to turn around trains, which would reduce capacity by 25%. While operating all 4 trains to Utica Avenue would have obviated the problem, the IRT did not have enough cars to run such a service. Instead, the Transit Commission accepted the IRT's plan to allocate 70 new cars to West Side express service to Brooklyn.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35414788/the-standard-union/|title=Orders I.R.T. to Improve Service|date=November 17, 1924|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Express service along Eastern Parkway would start at the earliest in February 1925 when additional new cars arrived.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35414740/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Hundred I.R.T. Cars To Bring Big Relief In Eastern Parkway: New Equipment, Recently Delivered, Will Increase Service 30 Per Cent. On Important Borough Lines, Commissioner McAneny Announces. Opening of Express Service Between Utica and Atlantic Aves. Off 3 Months.|date=November 17, 1924|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBeginning on November 4, 1925, 4 trains were extended from Atlantic Avenue to [[Crown Heights\u2013Utica Avenue (IRT Eastern Parkway Line)|Crown Heights\u2013Utica Avenue]] during rush hours, from 6:30 to 9:30 a.m. and 5 and 7 p.m., allowing for the introduction of express service along this section of the [[IRT Eastern Parkway Line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pudl.princeton.edu/sheetreader.php?obj=f5217622-5c01-49b6-b3d1-bef13f813a0a|title=Increased I.R.T. Subway Service in Brooklyn|last=|first=|date=November 1925|website=pudl.princeton.edu|publisher=Interborough Rapid Transit Company|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46595852/the-standard-union/|title=At Least I.R.T. Expresses Will Run Under Parkway: Two Tracks Will End Their Long Career of Idleness a Week from Wednesday.|date=October 25, 1925|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This extension was made possible by the delivery of the last of 350 new steel cars.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35415064/the-standard-union/|title=More I.R.T. Trains For Rush Hours To Operate Tomorrow: Brooklyn Gets Improved Service at cost of $3,000,000\u2014President Hedley Makes Inspection Trip.|date=November 3, 1925|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The increased service required 80 cars, or eight trains of ten cars each.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46596083/times-union/|title=I.R.T. Will Start Express Service In Boro Nov. 4: Ninety New Cars Added on Flatbush Ave. and Eastern Parkway Lines. Rush Hour Aid First. Three Million Dollar Outlay Will Mean 20 to 100 P.C. Better Handling of Crowds.|date=October 25, 1925|work=Brooklyn Times Union|access-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOn November 23, 1927, evening 4 service was extended from Atlantic Avenue to Utica Avenue between 7:14 and 8 p.m.. After the Transit Commission determined that this was not a sufficient increase in service, it announced on November 26 that evening 4 service to Utica Avenue would continue until 1 a.m.. This change took place on December 5, and increased service between Atlantic Avenue and Utica Avenue by 100%.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46594743/times-union/|title=100 P.C. Increase In I.R.T. Service: More Trains on Schedule Between Atlantic and Utica Avenues at Night.|date=November 27, 1927|work=Brooklyn Times Union|access-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The following year, midday 4 service also went to Utica Avenue.<ref name=\"erictb.info\" />\n\nAs of 1934, 4 trains ran from Woodlawn to Utica Avenue weekday rush and Saturday morning peak and afternoon, to Atlantic Avenue weekday midday, Saturday morning after the peak, and late nights, and to South Ferry evenings and Sundays. Trains ran express in Manhattan except during late nights, and in Brooklyn. This was the first time the 6 became the Pelham Shuttle between Pelham Bay Park and 125th Street\u2013Lexington Avenue.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOn August 20, 1938, Saturday morning after the peak service was extended to Utica Avenue.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Under the New York City Board of Transportation===\n\nBeginning on May 10, 1946, all 4 trains were made express during late nights running on 12 minute headways as the 6 went back to Brooklyn Bridge during that time. Previously 4 trains ran local from 12:30 to 5:30am. At this time 4 trains terminated at Atlantic Avenue.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1946/05/09/100997388.pdf|title = 24-Hour Express Service on IRT To Become Effective at Midnight|last = |first = |date = May 9, 1946|work = |access-date = February 21, 2016|via = |newspaper = New York Times}}</ref><ref name=\"BOT-1949\">{{Cite book|title=Report for the three and one-half years ending June 30, 1949.|date=1949|publisher=New York City Board of Transportation|hdl = 2027/mdp.39015023094926}}</ref>\n\nBeginning on December 16, 1946, trains were extended from Atlantic Avenue to New Lots Avenue during late nights, running express between Atlantic and Franklin Avenues.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1946/12/12/305817632.pdf|title = City to Increase Subway Service On the IRT and BMT Lines Today|last = |first = |date = December 12, 1946|work = |access-date = February 21, 2016|via = |newspaper = New York Times}}</ref>\n\nThe [[New York City Board of Transportation]], a predecessor to the [[New York City Transit Authority]], began to introduce replacements to older subway cars beginning with the [[R12 (New York City Subway car)|R12]] cars in 1948. With these cars, numbers were publicly designated to the former IRT lines. Lexington\u2013Jerome trains were assigned the number 4. By 1964, all cars had the route numbers on them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thejoekorner.com/lines/suball-frame.htm|title=Line Names|website=thejoekorner.com|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1950, Saturday morning service was cut back to South Ferry.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nStarting on December 15, 1950, four 4 trains began operating during rush hours to [[Flatbush Avenue\u2013Brooklyn College (IRT Nostrand Avenue Line)|Flatbush Avenue]] on the [[IRT Nostrand Avenue Line|Nostrand Avenue Line]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1950/12/15/313761962.pdf|title=Brooklyn I.R.T. Change; 4 Lexington Avenue Expresses to Serve Flatbush Station|date=December 15, 1950|work=The New York Times|newspaper=|access-date=February 22, 2016|url-status=live|via=}}</ref> Also on that day, weekday midday service was cut back from Atlantic Avenue to South Ferry. Additionally, on January 18, 1952, 4 service to Atlantic Avenue during weekday middays was restored.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1952/01/10/93341886.pdf|title = Changes on I.R.T. Set: Additional Express Service on Brooklyn, Flushing Lines Day|last = |first = |date = January 10, 1952|work = |access-date = January 25, 2016|via = |newspaper = New York Times}}</ref>\n\n===Under the New York City Transit Authority===\n\nOn March 19, 1954, late-night service in Brooklyn became local, but resumed operating express between Atlantic and Franklin Avenues on June 29, 1956.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nOn May 3, 1957, the weekday rush trains to Flatbush Avenue were discontinued, while at the same time evening, Saturday and Sunday afternoon trains were extended to Utica Avenue, while Sunday morning trains were extended to Atlantic Avenue.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nStarting on March 1, 1960, late-night 4 trains resumed making all stops in Manhattan; this was the first time the 4 and 6 ran local in Manhattan together late nights. This arrangement ended on October 17, 1965, when the 4 went back express in Manhattan late nights.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nBeginning on April 8, 1960, nearly all AM rush hour 4 trains ran to Flatbush Avenue, and PM rush hour 4 trains alternated between Flatbush and Utica Avenues. During weekday evenings and late nights 4 trains also went to Flatbush Avenue, making all stops in Brooklyn.<ref name=\"erictb.info\" />\n\nAs a result of the opening of the main portion of the [[Chrystie Street Connection]] along the [[Manhattan Bridge]] on November 26, 1967, the 4 train was color-coded magenta under the first color scheme. The color coding of lines was introduced as a matter of having a universal system of signage and nomenclature.\n\nBy 1972, the 4 began to skip 138th Street weekdays during rush hours in the peak direction which it continues to do (AM to Manhattan and PM from there). At that time, the 4 went to Atlantic Avenue at all times, but was extended to Utica Avenue rush hours running express in Brooklyn along Eastern Parkway. Select 4 trains also ran to Flatbush Avenue rush hours as well running express between Atlantic and Franklin Avenues, and late-night service made all stops in Brooklyn to Flatbush Avenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycsubway.org/perl/caption.pl?/img/maps/system_1972.jpg|title=1972 New York City Subway Map|last=|first=|date=1972|website=nycsubway.org|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 1976, Sunday morning trains were extended to Utica Avenue, running express in Brooklyn.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nEffective June 1979, the 4 train assumed its current line color of forest green as a result of a nomenclature update to assign colors to a trunk line, plus line colors not serving Manhattan.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nBeginning on January 13, 1980, all 4 trains resumed operating local in Manhattan during late night hours to replace the {{NYCS|6}}, which again became the Pelham Shuttle between [[125th Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|125th Street]] and [[Pelham Bay Park (IRT Pelham Line)|Pelham Bay Park]].<ref name=\"erictb.info\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 1979|title=January 1980 IRT Service Changes|url=|journal=New York Division Bulletin|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> This service cut affected 15,000 riders, and was criticized by Manhattan Borough President [[Andrew Stein]] as no public hearing was held.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/433946217/?terms=%22subway%22%2B%22service%2Bcut%22|title=Suit seeks to bar cutbacks on Lexington Ave. subways|last=|first=|date=January 11, 1980|work=New York Daily News|access-date=August 14, 2018|page=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 10, 1983, rush hour 4 trains were rerouted from Flatbush Avenue to Utica Avenue, and late evening and late night and Sunday morning service was rerouted from Flatbush Avenue to New Lots Avenue, making all local stops.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=July 1983|title=New IRT Schedules - Increased Service to Flatbush Avenue|url=|journal=New York Division Bulletin|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fultonhistory.com/highlighter/highlight-for-xml?altUrl=https%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Amsterdam%2520News%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Amsterdam%2520News%25201983%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Amsterdam%2520News%25201983%252000253_1.pdf%23xml%3Dhttps%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffa28002b6%26DocId%3D6932839%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520X%26HitCount%3D11%26hits%3D5fa%2B5fb%2B5fc%2B5fd%2B5fe%2B5ff%2B600%2B601%2B602%2B603%2B604%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&uri=https%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FNewspaper%252024%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Amsterdam%2520News%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Amsterdam%2520News%25201983%2FNew%2520York%2520NY%2520Amsterdam%2520News%25201983%252000253_1.pdf&xml=https%3A%2F%2Ffultonhistory.com%2FdtSearch%2Fdtisapi6.dll%3Fcmd%3Dgetpdfhits%26u%3Dffffffffa28002b6%26DocId%3D6932839%26Index%3DZ%253a%255cDISK%2520X%26HitCount%3D11%26hits%3D5fa%2B5fb%2B5fc%2B5fd%2B5fe%2B5ff%2B600%2B601%2B602%2B603%2B604%2B%26SearchForm%3D%252fFulton%255fform%252ehtml%26.pdf&openFirstHlPage=false|title=Notice of Public Hearing|last=|first=|date=February 26, 1983|work=New York Amsterdam News|access-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 1988, weekday midday 4 trains were extended from Atlantic Avenue to Utica Avenue, made possible by the termination of 5 service at Bowling Green.<ref name=\"1989Changes\" /><ref name=\"erictb.info\" /> In addition, service was increased 50% during evenings between 8 p.m. and midnight, on Saturday afternoon and on Sunday between 10 a.m. and 7 p.m. In January 1989, during middays, southbound service resumed operating express between Franklin Avenue and Utica Avenue following the elimination of 5 train layups.<ref name=\"1989Changes\" />\n\nLate night express service was reinstated from January 21, 1990 to October 5 of that year, as a result of the 6 being extended back to Brooklyn Bridge during that time.<ref name=\"1989Changes\">*{{Cite book|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/46694885825/in/album-72157706539432321/|title=Annual Report on 1989 Rapid Routes Schedules and Service Planning|last=|first=|date=June 1, 1990|publisher=New York City Transit Authority, Operations Planning Department|year=|isbn=|location=|page=26}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/46694885115/in/album-72157706539432321/|title=Annual Report on 1989 Rapid Routes Schedules and Service Planning|last=|first=|date=June 1, 1990|publisher=New York City Transit Authority, Operations Planning Department|year=|isbn=|location=|page=27}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/40644004553/in/album-72157706539432321/|title=Annual Report on 1989 Rapid Routes Schedules and Service Planning|last=|first=|date=June 1, 1990|publisher=New York City Transit Authority, Operations Planning Department|year=|isbn=|location=|page=28}}\n</ref> While late night 6 service to Brooklyn Bridge was permanently restored on October 3, 1999, the 4 continued to run local at those times, providing Lexington Avenue local stations service every ten minutes.<ref name=\"1999Change\">\n* {{cite book|title=May 1999 NYC Transit Committee Agenda|date=May 13, 1999|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 13, 2020|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/48536123271/in/photostream/|page=144}}\n* {{cite book|title=May 1999 NYC Transit Committee Agenda|date=May 13, 1999|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 13, 2020|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/48536270792/in/photostream/|page=145-146}}\n* {{cite book|title=May 1999 NYC Transit Committee Agenda|date=May 13, 1999|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 13, 2020|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/48536269727/in/photostream/|page=147}}\n* {{cite book|title=May 1999 NYC Transit Committee Agenda|date=May 13, 1999|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 13, 2020|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/48536268767/in/photostream/|page=148}}\n* {{cite book|title=May 1999 NYC Transit Committee Agenda|date=May 13, 1999|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 13, 2020|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/127872292@N06/48536267922/in/photostream/|page=149}}</ref>\n\n=== Recent changes ===\n[[File: Manhattan bound R142 4 train enters Yankee Stadium.jpg|thumb|Manhattan-bound 4 train of [[R142 (New York City Subway car)|R142s]] entering [[161st Street\u2013Yankee Stadium (New York City Subway)|161st Street\u2013Yankee Stadium]]]]\n\nFrom April 2000 to August 2001, midday 4 service was temporarily cut back from Utica Avenue to Atlantic Avenue to accommodate the rebuilding of the [[IRT New Lots Line]].<ref>{{Citation|url=|title=Timetable for subway service on the 4 Train Effective Spring 2000|last=|first=|date=April 2000|website=|publisher=New York City Transit|access-date=}}</ref> 3 train service was split into two sections to allow for the line to be rebuilt, with transfers available at Utica Avenue. Work took place on weekday middays between 10 a.m. and 3 p.m., and New Lots service operated in one of three ways: shuttle buses replaced trains, all trains operated in both directions on a single track, or shuttle trains ran. 4 trains terminated at Atlantic Avenue when shuttle or single-track trains were in operation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.nyc.ny.us/nyct/service/subsrvno.htm#FourLine|title=Weekly Subway Service Advisories Updated Nov 9, 2000|last=|first=|date=2000-11-09|website=mta.nyc.ny.us|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001109144600/http://www.mta.nyc.ny.us/nyct/service/subsrvno.htm#FourLine|archive-date=November 9, 2000|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nFrom June 8, 2009, to June 26, 2009, New York City Transit conducted a pilot program for express Jerome Avenue Line service. During a one hour period, four morning weekday rush hour trains from Woodlawn only stopped at Mosholu Parkway, Burnside Avenue and 149th Street\u2013Grand Concourse before resuming regular service in Manhattan and Brooklyn. The express was expected to save riders 3.5 minutes. The pilot was made possible due to signaling upgrades to the line's center track made as part of the 2005\u20142009 Metropolitan Transportation Authority Capital Program.<ref name=\"MTA-June2009Pilot\">{{cite press release|title=MTA New York City Transit Pilots Bronx Express Service Along the Jerome Ave. Line|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/mta-new-york-city-transit-pilots-bronx-express-service-along-jerome-ave|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|date=June 4, 2009|accessdate=June 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/nyct/service/events/BronxExpressPilot.htm|title=Bronx Express Pilot Program June 8 to 26, Monday to Friday, 7 AM to 8 AM|last=|first=|date=June 10, 2009|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610212200/http://www.mta.info/nyct/service/events/BronxExpressPilot.htm|archivedate=June 10, 2009|access-date=September 23, 2016|df=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2009, select Bronx bound 4 trains began running express from 167th Street to Burnside Avenue to terminate at the latter station before running out of service to the Jerome Yard.\n\nOn October 26, 2009, another 4 express pilot program was implemented based on the success of the first and ran until December 11, 2009. This program was the same as the one in June except that express trains stopped at [[Bedford Park Boulevard\u2013Lehman College (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|Bedford Park Boulevard\u2013Lehman College]]. This express service was expected to cut runtime by four minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/nyct/service/events/BronxExpressPilot.htm|title=Bronx Express Phase II October 26 to December 11, Monday to Friday, 7 AM to 8:20 AM|last=|first=|date=November 22, 2009|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122100652/http://www.mta.info/nyct/service/events/BronxExpressPilot.htm|archivedate=November 22, 2009|access-date=September 23, 2016|df=}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of planned repairs to [[Hurricane Sandy]]-related damage in the Clark Street Tube, which carries the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]], on weekends from June 17, 2017 to June 24, 2018, the 4 was extended to New Lots Avenue on weekends, making local stops in Brooklyn south of [[Nevins Street (IRT Eastern Parkway Line)|Nevins Street]] in place of the {{NYCS|3}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/161212_1000_Transit.pdf|title=Transit & Bus Committee Meeting December 2016|last=|first=|date=December 12, 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|pages=PDF\u2013169 to PDF\u2013175|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161210041234/http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/161212_1000_Transit.pdf|archivedate=December 10, 2016|accessdate=December 9, 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/sandy/sandy_recovery_work.htm|title=Clark St Tunnel Reconstruction Weekend Service Changes|last=|first=|date=June 8, 2017|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608184832/http://web.mta.info/sandy/sandy_recovery_work.htm|archive-date=June 8, 2017|access-date=May 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 17, 2019, New York City Transit cut weekday evening 3, 4 and 5 service in order to accommodate planned subway work. This change, which was approved by the MTA Board on June 27, 2019, started late night 4 service to New Lots Avenue, an hour earlier, at 10:30 p.m. instead of 11:30 p.m., replacing 3 service, which was cut back to [[Times Square\u201342nd Street/Port Authority Bus Terminal station|Times Square\u201342nd Street]]. These changes in service were expected to save the agency $0.9 million annually.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/190624_1030_Transit.pdf|title=Transit and Bus Committee Meeting June 2019|last=|first=|date=June 24, 2019|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|page=94-97|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://new.mta.info/document/9446|title=5 Subway Timetable Effective November 17, 2019|last=|first=|date=November 17, 2019|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Route ==\n\n=== Service pattern ===\nThe following table shows the lines used by the 4, with shaded boxes indicating the route at the specified times:<ref>{{NYCS const|serviceguide}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n! rowspan=2 | Line\n! rowspan=2 | From\n! rowspan=2 | To\n! rowspan=2 | Tracks\n! colspan=3 | Times\n|-\n! width=40 | all {{abbr|ex.|except}} nights\n! width=40 | late nights\n! width=40 | rush peak\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[IRT Jerome Avenue Line]] (full line)\n| [[Woodlawn (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|Woodlawn]]\n|[[183rd Street station (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|183rd Street]]\n| rowspan=2 | local\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:gray\" | &nbsp;\n| rowspan=2 style=\"background:gray\" | &nbsp;\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ddffdd;\" | Most trains\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Burnside Avenue station|Burnside Avenue]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[170th Street station (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|170th Street]]\n|-\n|express\n|&nbsp;\n|&nbsp;\n| style=\"background:yellow\" | Limited service ({{abbr|NB|northbound}} only)\n|-\n|[[167th Street station (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|167th Street]]\n|[[149th Street\u2013Grand Concourse (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|149th Street\u2013Grand Concourse]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |local\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:gray\" | &nbsp;\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:gray\" | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background:gray\" | &nbsp;\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |[[138th Street\u2013Grand Concourse (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|138th Street\u2013Grand Concourse]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |express\n|&nbsp;\n|&nbsp;\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:gray\" | &nbsp;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] (full line)\n|